
CRDs (Custom Resource Definitions) are the way that K8S lets 
you define your own objects that behave like built-in K8S 
objects.

Skupper examples are: Site, Link, Listener, Connector.

When Kubernetes 1.0 was introduced in July 2015, CRDs were 
not part of it. They were not introduced until 1.7 in June
2017, and went GA in 1.16 in Sep 2019.

It is possible to make a basic custom resource by supplying 
only YAML. That basically gives you some structured storage
that gets treated by K8S just like any of its own resources.
But that will *not* give you any behavior on the part of the
resource. Obviously.

An Operator is a collection of one or more CRDs plus the Controller code
that reconciles them. The CRDs are YAML that gets applied to the K8S
API Server, which creates Custom Resources from them. Our Controller
talks to K8S to put watches on the CRs. When anything changes in the
CRs the Controller gets notifications from K8S. It then determines if
the current state matches the desired state of the resources. If not,
it issues to K8S to correct the divergence. It continues performing this
'reconciliation' loop as long as the Pod runs.


